My coworker and I were having an argument which approach should we take when adding listeners to our ui component. We are considering two major options for adding support to listeners. For the sake of keeping it simple, lets say we have three events: on failure, on processing begin, and on processing end.

The first option we were thinking of was having an interface which declares on all the functions, i.e:

    /** General Listener. */
    public interface Listener {
      /** Called when processing begins. */
      void onProcessingBegin(EventInfo info);
    
      /** Called when processing ends with success. */
      void onProcessingSuccess();
    
      /** Called when processing ends with failure. */
      void onProcessingError(ErrorInfo error);
    }

Where the second option is to have a listener for each event separately:

    /** Begin Listener. */
    public interface ProcessingBeginListener {
      /** Called when processing begins. */
      void onProcessingBegin(EventInfo info);
    }

    /** Success Listener. */
    public interface ProcessingSuccessListener {
      /** Called when processing ends with success. */
      void onProcessingSuccess();
    }

    /** Failure Listener. */
    public interface ProcessingFailureListener {
      /** Called when processing ends with failure. */
      void onProcessingError(ErrorInfo error);
    }

I was wondering if there&#39;s any difference between these suggestions, and when should we prefer one over another. Any what is generally the best practice, and why?

Thanks.

